               <msContents>
                  <summary>This complete copy of the <title>Tuḥfat al-Aḥrār</title> (Gift of the
                     Noble) composed by Timurid-era poet <persName key="person_90042997"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/90042997/" xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">‘Abd al-Raḥmān
                        Jāmī (d. 1492)</persName> comprises the fifth of seven books in his
                     collection entitled <title>Haft Awrang</title> (Seven Thrones). A Safavid-era
                     scribe named <persName role="scr">Muḥammad bin Mullā Mīr al-Ḥusaynī
                        al-Ustādī</persName> completed this lavishly illuminated manuscript at the
                        <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1581-07-01" to="1581-07-08">end of
                        Jumādà I 989 (beg. Jul. 1581 CE)</date>. It subsequently made its way to
                     volume bears many seal impressions and notations indicating that it was
                     formerly held in the royal library of the Kings of <placeName
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502" key="place_7001502"
                        >Awadh</placeName> in <placeName
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001561" key="place_7001561"
                        >Lucknow</placeName>. </summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_520-item1">
                     <author key="person_90042997" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/90042997/"
                        change="#ids-cleanup">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">‘Abd al-Raḥman Jāmī, 1414-1492</persName>; <lb/>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa" type="foreign">عبد الرحمن جامی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <editor role="scr">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Muḥammad bin Mullā Mīr al-Ḥusaynī
                           al-Ustādī</persName>; <lb/>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa" type="foreign"> محمد بن ملا میر الحسینی
                           الاستادی</persName>
                     </editor>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_202">Tuḥfat al-Aḥrār</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_202">تحفة الاحرار</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmala"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio
                           1b):</locus> حامداً لمن جعل جنان کل عارف مخزن اسرار... </incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="78a" to="78a"> برگ ۷۸ر (folio 78a):</locus> مهر نه خاتمه این
                        خطاب * شد رقم خاتم تم الکتاب. </explicit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa"><locus from="78a" to="78a"> برگ ۷۸ر (folio
                           78a):</locus> تحریراً فی تاریخ اواخر شهر جمادی اول سنه ۹۷۹ کتبه محمد بن
                        ملا میر الحسینی الاستادی غفر ذنبه و ستر عیوبه. میدهد آخر فلکم چون بباد *
                        فاتحه شد عرضم زین سواد. </colophon>
                     <colophon>Completed by <persName role="scr">Muḥammad bin Mullā Mīr al-Ḥusaynī
                           al-Ustādī</persName> at the <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                           from="1581-07-01" to="1581-07-08">end of Jumādà I 989 (beg. Jul. 1581
                           CE)</date>.</colophon>

                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>For another copy of this text held in the Rylands see the <title>Haft
                           Awrang</title> (Seven Thrones) <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_26549">Persian MS
                           949</ref>. For a <title>Būstān</title> of Sa‘dī completed by the same
                        scribe in see Cambridge University Library <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_50"><idno>Add.
                              204</idno></ref>. For more on this scribe, see Bayānī.</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Textblock of cross-grained, heavily flocked, externally sized and
                           polished, buff-coloured <material>paper</material>, probably handmade in
                           the <placeName type="empire"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/6005089" key="place_6005089"
                              >Safavid Empire</placeName>, with ~9 laid lines per cm and no
                           discernible chain lines.</support>
                        <extent>
                           <measure unit="folio" quantity="78">78 folios, 7 flyleaves (ff. iv + 78 +
                              iii)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>221</height>
                              <width>136</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>149</height>
                              <width>70</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation xml:id="original">Hindu-Arabic numerals added to the upper-left
                           corners of the a sides, with folio <locus from="39Aa" to="39Aa"
                              >39Aa</locus> repeated twice, hence under by one.</foliation>
                        <collation> Primarily quaterions. 9IV(71)1IV-1(78)<catchwords>Catchwords
                              throughout most of the lower-left corners of the b
                           sides.</catchwords></collation>


                        <condition>In fair condition, with moderate water and insect damage and
                           historical repairs throughout.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1 2" ruledLines="12" n="mistara"> Written in 1 to 2 columns
                           with 12 lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand
                           guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink"> Written in clear
                           <material>black</material> nasta‘līq with <material>red</material>
                        subheaders by <persName role="scr">Muḥammad bin Mullā Mīr al-Ḥusaynī
                           al-Ustādī</persName>. </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="headpiece"><label>Illumination:</label> Folio <locus from="1b"
                           to="1b">1b</locus> bears a contemporaneous scalloped domed headpiece with
                        gilt palmette foliate scrollwork on a combination of solid gold and
                        ultramarine grounds, above a rectangular cartouche bearing a stylized
                        shikastah script <hi rend="italic">basmala</hi> on a gold ground, and
                        surmounted by nine vertical radiating lines.</decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="marginal"><label>Gold spray:</label> Central text finely
                        sprayed with gold ink prior to writing.</decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="marginal"><label>Ruling:</label> Margins ruled in
                           <material>gold</material> outlined with thin black single black internal
                        and double external lines, with internal single lines of green verdigris
                        (many corroded and breaking on the inner margins), red, and ultramarine,
                        with comparatively thin internal single gold lines outline by thin black
                        single lines, and all surrounded by single ultramarine lines.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Marginalia:</label> Notes in various hands written between the lines and
                     in the margins.<lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label>
                     <list type="bulleted">
                        <item>The <locus from="1a" to="ia">right flyleaf a side (f. ia)</locus>
                           bears the title in nasta‘līq script, probably in the hand of <persName
                              role="wst" key="person_f6587">Muhīn Dās</persName>, assistant to
                           former owner <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo"
                              change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton</persName>. </item>
                        <item>Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears several notations:
                              <list type="bulleted">
                              <item>
                                 <label>Top:</label> the title written in naskh script.</item>
                              <item>
                                 <label>Middle:</label> Left: <q>81 leaves</q>, <q>Number 57</q>,
                                 and an undated shikastah inspection note underneath by one
                                    <persName role="ato ins">Munshī Muḥammad ‘Ali</persName>, which
                                 probably pertains to Awadh (Oude) royal library: <q>من اهتمام فدوى
                                    منشى محمد علي</q></item>
                              <item>An unsigned inspection notation dated <date
                                    calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1846-03-03">5 Rabī‘ I 1262 AH (3
                                    Mar. 1846)</date>, probably by an unidentified Awadh royal
                                 library attendant to King of Awadh <persName role=" seal fmo"
                                    key="person_9680150325559110090006"
                                    ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/9680150325559110090006/">Amjad ‘Alī
                                    Shāh</persName>, who similary signed other volumes held
                                 there.</item>
                           </list>
                        </item>
                        <item> Folio <locus from="78b" to="78b">78b</locus> bears a notation next to
                           the seal of <persName cert="medium" role=" seal fmo ins" key="person_f8490">Farīdūn
                              Khān</persName> (no. 5), hence probably in his hand, in which he
                           describes his purchase of the volume for 150 Rupees from <persName
                              role="fmo" key="person_f8491">Ḥajjī Khalīl ‘Arab</persName> (or Jalīl ‘Arab) on <date
                              calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1741-02-21">Wednesday, 5 Ẕī-al-Ḥijjah
                              1153 AH (21 Feb. 1741 CE)</date>:<lb/>
                           <q>بتاریخ پنجم ذیالحجة روز چهار شنبه سنه ۱۱۵۳ خجری نبوی بقیمت صد و پنجاه
                              روپیه خرید این از حاجی خلیل عرب با عبارت ازش تومان شب لعینت(؟)</q>
                        </item>
                     </list>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label> The <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                        to="Inner_back_cover">left doublure</locus>: <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca
                        Lindesiana</q> with pencilled shelfmark <q xml:lang="en">1/I</q>, and <q
                        xml:lang="en"><hi rend="strikethrough">Hamilton</hi> MSS No. <hi
                           rend="strikethrough">437</hi></q>, with the name and number crossed out
                     and <q xml:lang="en">Persian</q> and <q xml:lang="en">520</q> written aside. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1737" notAfter="1835">
                        <p>Probably rebound in a hydrid British-Indian style in <placeName
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7002481" key="place_7002481"
                              >Multan</placeName> for former owner <persName type="supplied"
                              key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">George William
                              Hamilton</persName> between <date cert="high" calendar="#Gregorian"
                              from="1858" to="1862">1858 and 1862</date>.</p>
                        <p>Resewn at two stations, unsupported. Edges trimmed, the <locus
                              from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> coloured black, and chevron
                           endbands of green and red silk threads twined at <locus from="Head"
                              to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus>.
                           Covered in full maroon-coloured goatskin <material>leather</material>
                           over <material>pasteboards</material>, without a flap but with squares at
                           the edges and defined joints (type III binding per Déroche). Internal
                           doublures lined with the same leather, their excess widths adhered as
                           hinges to the flyleaves to connect the cover to the text, with strips of
                           paper, decoratively cut with zig-zags along one edges, applied over top
                           to disguise the joins.</p>

                        <decoNote type="binding">Board margins painted black with foliate palmette
                           vines, similar to Rylands <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7029"
                                 ><idno>Persian MS 533</idno></ref>, <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7030">534</ref>,
                           and <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7035"
                              >539</ref>. Title handwritten in nasta‘līq script on the <locus
                              from="Spine" to="Spine">spine</locus> within a hand-painted gold
                           cartouche.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>228</height>
                              <width>141</width>
                              <depth>22</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Binding in fair but stable condition, with blackened upper
                           corners due to water damage and remnants of a paper cover adhered to the
                           interior doublures.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <summary>Four vermilion library seal impressions on folio <locus from="1a"
                           to="1a">1a</locus>, all intaglio-carved in nasta‘līq script in two
                        stacked lines, of the kings of <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502" key="place_7001502">Awadh
                           (Oude)</placeName>, with three repeated again on <locus from="78b"
                           to="78b">78b</locus>, along with a large oval <material>black</material>
                        impression.</summary>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>1:</label> A large, rare, unidentified rectangular library seal,
                           surmounted by two tigers supporting the crown of Awadh, double-ruled,
                           possibly of <persName cert="medium" role="fmo seal"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/2049153653237255900003"
                              key="person_2049153653237255900003">Ghazī al-Dīn Ḥaydar Shāh (b. 1769,
                              Nawwab r. 1814–1818; King of Awadh r. 1818–1827)</persName>, given the
                           date <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1821" notAfter="1822">1237
                              AH (1821–1822 CE)</date> underneath. It possibly reads:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="fa"> رونق صد مهر دفاتر ثلثین * مهر کتب خانهٔ شاه زمین،
                              ١٢۳۷</q><lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="en"><hi rend="italic">Rawnaq-i ṣad muhr-i dafātir s̤alas̱īn;
                                 muhur-i kitāb khānah-'i Shāh-i zamīn</hi>, <date
                                 calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1821" notAfter="1822"
                                 >1237</date> hijrī</q> (<q xml:lang="en">The seal of the library of
                              the land is as lustrous as a hundred seals upon thirty volumes, <date
                                 calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1821" notAfter="1822">1237
                                 AH</date></q>).<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>67</height>
                              <width>55</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>2:</label> Rectangular library seal of <persName role="fmo seal"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/265857376" key="person_265857376">Nāṣir
                              al-Dīn Ḥaydar Shāh (b. 1803, r. 1827–1837)</persName>, in two stacked
                           cartouches, double-ruled, dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                              notBefore="1828" notAfter="1829">1244 AH (1828–29 CE)</date>, and
                           inscribed with his title <addName type="epithet"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/265857376" key="person_265857376">Sulaymān
                              Jāh</addName>:<lb/><q xml:lang="fa"> خوش است مهر کتبخانه سلیمان جاه *
                              بهر کتاب مزین چو نقش بسم الله، ١٢۴۴</q><lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="en"><hi rend="italic">Khvush ast muhur-i kitābkhānah-'i
                                 Sulaymān Jāh bahr-i kitāb; muzayyin chaw naqsh-i basmallah</hi>,
                                 <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1828-07-14"
                                 notAfter="1829-07-02">1244 </date></q> (<q xml:lang="en">The seal
                              of the library of Sulaymān Jāh is good; it embellishes the book like
                              the design of a <hi rend="italic">basmallah</hi>, <date
                                 calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1828-07-14"
                                 notAfter="1829-07-02">1244 AH</date></q>).<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>17</height>
                              <width>37</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>3:</label> Rectangular library seal, surmounted by the royal
                           emblem of Awadh, of <persName role=" seal fmo"
                              key="person_9680150325559110090006"
                              ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/9680150325559110090006/">Amjad ‘Alī Shāh
                              (b. 1801, r. 1842–1847)</persName>, dotted-ruled and dated <date
                              calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1844-01-22" notAfter="1845-01-09"
                              >1260 AH (1844–45 CE)</date>:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="fa">ناسخ هر مهر شد چون شد مزین بر کتاب * خاتم امجد علی شاه
                              زمان عالیجناب، ١٢٦٠</q><lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"><hi rend="italic">Nāsukh har muhur shud chun
                                 shud muzayyin bar kitāb; khātim-i Amjad ‘Alī Shāh zamān-i
                                 ‘Ālījanāb</hi>, <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                                 notBefore="1844-01-22" notAfter="1845-01-09">1260</date></q> (<q
                              xml:lang="en">Every [prior] seal became cancelled since the book
                              became embellished by the seal of Amjad ‘Alī Shāh in the era of his
                              Sublime Majesty, <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1844-01-22"
                                 notAfter="1845-01-09">1260 AH</date></q>).<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>53</height>
                              <width>45</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>4:</label> Library seal, surmounted by the royal emblem Awadh, of
                              <persName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/305855167" role=" seal fmo"
                              key="person_305855167">Wājid ‘Alī Shāh (b. 1822, r.
                              1847–1856)</persName>, single-ruled and dated <date
                              calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1846" notAfter="1847">1262 AH
                              (1847 CE)</date>:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="fa"> خاتم واجد علی سلطان عالم بر کتاب * ثابت و پر نور بادا
                              تا فروغ آفتاب، ١٢۶۲ </q><lb/><q xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"><hi
                                 rend="italic">Khātim-i Wājid ‘Alī, Sulṭān-i ‘Ālam bar kitāb, s̄abit
                                 va pur nūr bādā tā farūgh-i āftāb</hi>, 1262</q> (<q xml:lang="en"
                              >The seal of Wājid ‘Alī, Sulṭān of the World, upon the book shall be
                              permanent and as bright as sunlight, <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                                 notBefore="1844-01-22" notAfter="1845-01-09">1262 AH</date></q>).<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>41</height>
                              <width>26</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="oval">
                        <p><label>5:</label>A large black oval seal impression, intaglio-carved in
                           three stacked lines read from bottom upwards, double-ruled, of a former
                           owner or associate named <persName cert="medium" role=" seal asn" key="person_f8490">Farīdūn
                              Khān</persName> dated <q xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"><date
                                 calendar="#Hirji-qamari" from="1731" to="1732">regnal year 13 [of
                                 Muḥammad Shāh] (1144 AH/1731–1732 CE)</date></q>:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="fa">فریدون خان خان زاد بادشاه محمد شاه غزی سنه ۱۳</q><lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>32</height>
                              <width>44</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
