               <history>
                  <origin>Probably completed by <persName role="scr">Muḥammad bin Mullā Mīr
                        al-Ḥusaynī al-Ustādī</persName> in the <origPlace type="empire"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/6005089" key="place_6005089">Safavid
                        Empire</origPlace>
                     <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1581-07-01" to="1581-07-08">end of
                        Jumādà I 989 (beg. Jul. 1581 CE)</origDate>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>Probably purchased by <persName cert="medium" role="fmo asn seal"
                     key="person_f8490">Farīdūn Khān</persName> for 150 Rupees from <persName role="fmo"
                        key="person_f8491">Ḥajjī Khalīl ‘Arab</persName> (or Jalīl ‘Arab) on <date
                           calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1741-02-21">Wednesday, 5 Ẕī-al-Ḥijjah
                           1153 AH (21 Feb. 1741 CE)</date>, as per a note adjacent to his seal
                        impression on folio <locus from="78b" to="78b">78b</locus>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Previously held in the royal library of <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502">Awadh</placeName> in
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502"
                           key="place_7001502">Awadh (Oude)</placeName>, as indicated by dated
                        library notations on folios <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> and <locus
                           from="78b" to="78b">78b</locus>, together with seal impressions of the
                        Kings of Awadh <persName type="person" role="fmo seal"
                           key="person_265857376" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/265857376">Nāṣir al-Dīn
                           Ḥaydar Shāh (b. 1803, r. 1827–1837)</persName>, <persName
                           key="person_41360366" role="fmo seal" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/41360366"
                           >Muḥammad ‘Alī Shāh (b. 1777, r. 1837–1842)</persName>, <persName
                           role="fmo" key="person_9680150325559110090006"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/9680150325559110090006"> Amjad ‘Alī Shāh (b.
                           1801, r. 1842–1847)</persName>, and <persName type="person"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/305855167" role="fmo seal"
                           key="person_305855167">Wājid ‘Alī Shāh (b. 1822, r.
                        1847–1856)</persName>, then presumably looted during India's First War of
                        Independence, when British soldiers ransacked the Qaisarbagh palace and
                        library on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1858-03-15">15 March
                           1858</date> (see Wolseley's memoir).</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by <persName type="supplied"
                           key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George
                           William Hamilton (1807-1868)</persName> who served in <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                           >India</placeName>
                        <date from="1823" to="1867"> from 1823 to 1867</date>, latterly as
                        Commissioner in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535"
                           >Delhi</placeName>. He acquired over a thousand Indian and Persian
                        manuscripts, from which the <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252"
                           >British Museum</orgName> purchased 352 from his widow, <persName
                           key="person_f8470" role="fmo">Charlotte Logie Hamilton
                           (1817–1893)</persName>, now held in the <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>
                        <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058"> Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> purchased the remainder of Hamilton's collection
                        in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1868">1868</date>. </p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                           Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                           key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
